---
import GuidaLayout from '../../../layouts/GuidaLayout.astro';
import FAQFisarmonica from '../../../components/ui/FAQFisarmonica.astro';
import { SITE } from '../../../config';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = "Tax Wedge Italy 2026: How the Cuneo Fiscale Cut Works";
const description = "Italy's structural tax wedge cut explained: who qualifies, how much you save by income level, where it shows on your payslip, and differences from prior years.";

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'Guides', url: `${SITE.url}/en/guides/` },
  { name: 'Tax Wedge 2026', url: `${SITE.url}/en/guides/tax-wedge-2026/` },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Who is eligible for the 2026 tax wedge benefit?',
    answer: 'The cuneo fiscale 2026 applies to all <strong>dependent employees</strong> (lavoratori dipendenti) with annual employment income up to &euro;40,000. This includes both private-sector and public-sector employees, as well as workers on fixed-term contracts. Freelancers, self-employed workers, and those on the flat-rate regime (regime forfettario) are not eligible. The benefit is applied automatically by your employer through payroll &mdash; you do not need to file a separate application.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much is the tax wedge benefit worth?',
    answer: 'The amount depends on your income level. For incomes up to &euro;20,000, the benefit is a percentage-based bonus (from 7.1% down to 4.8% depending on the income sub-band), which can be worth up to roughly &euro;1,000&ndash;&euro;1,100 per year. For incomes between &euro;20,001 and &euro;32,000, the benefit is a flat &euro;1,000 additional deduction. Between &euro;32,001 and &euro;40,000, the &euro;1,000 deduction decreases linearly until it reaches zero at &euro;40,000. On a monthly payslip with 13 pay periods, the &euro;1,000 benefit translates to roughly &euro;77 extra per month.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does the tax wedge appear on my payslip?',
    answer: 'The tax wedge benefit appears on your busta paga (payslip) as a separate line item. For incomes up to &euro;20,000, it is shown as a non-taxable bonus (similar to how the old esonero contributivo appeared). For incomes above &euro;20,000, it appears as an additional tax deduction that reduces the IRPEF withheld. Either way, the effect is the same: a higher net amount credited to your bank account. You will typically see it labelled as "beneficio cuneo fiscale" or "ulteriore detrazione L. 207/2024" on the payslip.',
  },
];
---

<GuidaLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  datePublished="2026-01-15"
  dateModified="2026-05-01"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  faqs={faqs}
  lang={lang}
>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <Fragment slot="toc">
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><a href="#what-is-the-tax-wedge" class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-brand transition-colors">What Is the Tax Wedge?</a></li>
      <li><a href="#from-temporary-to-structural" class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-brand transition-colors">From Temporary to Structural</a></li>
      <li><a href="#how-the-2026-mechanism-works" class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-brand transition-colors">How the 2026 Mechanism Works</a></li>
      <li><a href="#benefit-amounts-by-income" class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-brand transition-colors">Benefit Amounts by Income Level</a></li>
      <li><a href="#faq" class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-brand transition-colors">Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
    </ul>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Article content -->

  <h2 id="what-is-the-tax-wedge">What Is the Tax Wedge?</h2>

  <p>
    The <strong>tax wedge</strong> (cuneo fiscale) is the difference between what an employer pays for an employee and what the employee actually takes home. It includes social security contributions (both employer and employee portions) and income tax. In Italy, the tax wedge has historically been among the highest in the OECD, often exceeding 45% of total labour costs.
  </p>
  <p>
    To address this and boost workers' take-home pay without raising gross salaries, the Italian government has introduced a series of measures to <strong>cut the tax wedge</strong> (taglio del cuneo fiscale). The latest and most significant version was made permanent in the 2025 Budget Law (Legge di Bilancio 2025, L. 207/2024), taking full effect from January 2026.
  </p>

  <h2 id="from-temporary-to-structural">From Temporary to Structural</h2>

  <p>
    The tax wedge reduction has gone through several iterations:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>2024&ndash;2025:</strong> a temporary contribution exemption (esonero contributivo) reduced the employee's INPS rate by 6&ndash;7 percentage points for incomes up to &euro;35,000. This was not a tax cut but a social-security discount, meaning it could potentially affect future pension accruals.</li>
    <li><strong>2026 onward:</strong> the mechanism was replaced with a <strong>fiscal</strong> (tax-based) benefit. Instead of reducing INPS contributions, it now operates either as a non-taxable bonus or as an additional IRPEF deduction. This preserves full pension contribution records while still increasing net pay.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The shift from a contribution exemption to a fiscal mechanism is important for expats to understand: your INPS contribution base is no longer reduced, which means your future Italian pension (if applicable) is calculated on the full gross salary.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how-the-2026-mechanism-works">How the 2026 Mechanism Works</h2>

  <p>
    The 2026 cuneo fiscale has two distinct arms depending on your income level:
  </p>

  <h3>For income up to &euro;20,000: percentage-based bonus</h3>
  <p>
    Workers earning up to &euro;20,000 per year receive a <strong>non-taxable bonus</strong> calculated as a percentage of their employment income (reddito da lavoro dipendente). The percentage varies by sub-band:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Up to &euro;8,500:</strong> 7.1% of employment income</li>
    <li><strong>&euro;8,501 to &euro;15,000:</strong> 5.3% of employment income</li>
    <li><strong>&euro;15,001 to &euro;20,000:</strong> 4.8% of employment income</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This bonus is exempt from IRPEF and does not count toward taxable income. It is paid directly through payroll each month.
  </p>

  <h3>For income &euro;20,001 to &euro;40,000: additional deduction</h3>
  <p>
    Workers in this income range receive an <strong>additional IRPEF deduction</strong> (ulteriore detrazione):
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>&euro;20,001 to &euro;32,000:</strong> flat &euro;1,000 deduction</li>
    <li><strong>&euro;32,001 to &euro;40,000:</strong> the &euro;1,000 deduction decreases linearly, calculated as 1,000 &times; (40,000 &minus; income) / 8,000</li>
    <li><strong>Above &euro;40,000:</strong> no benefit</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="benefit-amounts-by-income">Benefit Amounts by Income Level</h2>

  <p>
    Here is a quick reference showing the approximate annual benefit at various income levels:
  </p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b-2 border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
          <th class="py-3 pr-4 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Annual income</th>
          <th class="py-3 px-4 text-center font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Mechanism</th>
          <th class="py-3 pl-4 text-right font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Approximate annual benefit</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;10,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Bonus (5.3%)</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">&asymp; &euro;530</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;18,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Bonus (4.8%)</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">&asymp; &euro;864</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;25,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Deduction</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">&euro;1,000</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;30,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Deduction</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">&euro;1,000</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;36,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Deduction (phase-out)</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">&asymp; &euro;500</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">&euro;40,000</td>
          <td class="py-3 px-4 text-center text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">Phase-out complete</td>
          <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-right tabular-nums text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">&euro;0</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    To see exactly how the tax wedge affects your personal net salary, use our <a href="/en/">net salary calculator</a> &mdash; the cuneo fiscale benefit is included automatically.
  </p>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="not-prose">
    <FAQFisarmonica faqs={faqs} titolo="" lang={lang} />
  </div>

</GuidaLayout>
